— In the Below Example we Have Checked How Many Customers have Placed At least One Order


SELECT COUNT(distinct c.customer_id)
FROM orders o
INNER JOIN customers c
ON o.order_customer_id = c.customer_id;

+-------------------------------+
| count(distinct c.customer_id) |
+-------------------------------+
|                         12405 |
+-------------------------------+

There Are 12405 are the number of customers who have placed At least 1 order




OR

— Using SET Operations

SELECT COUNT(*) FROM (SELECT customer_id FROM customers INTERSECT SELECT order_customer_id FROM orders) c;

+----------+
| COUNT(*) |
+----------+
|    12405 |
+----------+








— In the Below Example we Have Checked How Many Customers have NOT Placed Any Order  [Using SET Operations]


SELECT COUNT(*) FROM (SELECT customer_id FROM customers EXCEPT SELECT order_customer_id FROM orders) c;

+----------+
| COUNT(*) |
+----------+
|       30 |
+----------+







— In the Below Example we Have Checked How Many Customers have NOT Placed Any Order  


IMP NOTE — INNER JOIN Will Not Work Here as it Only Shows Matching Records, So we will Have to Use Left Outer Join 



SELECT COUNT(*) FROM customers c LEFT OUTER JOIN orders o ON c.customer_id = o.order_customer_id WHERE o.order_customer_id is NULL;

+----------+
| COUNT(*) |
+----------+
|       30 |
+----------+













